753	what are the supreme court cases	  The first amendment to the United States Constitution guarantees the right to free speech. This amendment has been tested in a number of Supreme Court cases. One such case, Tinker v. Des Moines Independent Community School District, involved a group of students who were suspended from school for wearing black armbands in protest of the Vietnam War. The Supreme Court ruled in favor of the students, stating that their right to free speech had been violated.  Another Supreme Court case that tested the right to free speech was New York Times Co. v. Sullivan. In this case, the New York Times published an advertisement that criticized the police department in Montgomery, Alabama. The police department sued the New York Times for libel, and the case went all the way to the Supreme Court. The Supreme Court ruled in favor of the New York Times, stating that public officials could not sue for libel unless they could prove that the statements in the advertisement were false and that the New York Times had known they were false.

In 1905, the Wanderers were defeated by the Ottawa Silver Seven, and the Stanley Cup was awarded to the Ottawa club. The Ottawa club was then defeated by the Montreal Wanderers in 1906, and the Stanley Cup was awarded back to the Montreal Wanderers. In 1909, the Montreal Wanderers were defeated by the Ottawa Senators, and the Stanley Cup was awarded to the Ottawa club. The Ottawa club was then defeated by the Montreal Wanderers in 1910, and the Stanley Cup was awarded back to the Montreal Wanderers. In 1911, the Montreal Wanderers were defeated by the Quebec Bulldogs, and the Stanley Cup was awarded to the Quebec club. 1202	who was kate chopin	   Kate Chopin was born in 1850 to an upper-class family in St. Louis, Missouri. She was educated by nuns and later by private tutors. In 1871, she married Oscar Chopin, a cotton merchant. The couple had six children, but only two survived infancy. After Oscar's death in 1882, Chopin took up writing to support her family. She published her first story, "At the Cadian Ball," in 1892.  Kate Chopin was a feminist writer who explored the inner lives of women. Her stories and novels challenged the traditional views of women's roles and helped to advance the cause of women's rights. Her most famous work, The Awakening, was published in 1899 and was met with criticism and controversy. Chopin died in 1904.

Cathode rays are negatively charged particles that are emitted from the negative electrode (cathode) of a vacuum tube. Thomson found that the charge to mass ratio was always the same, regardless of the material from which the cathode rays were emitted. This led him to conclude that the cathode rays were made up of very small, negatively charged particles.

4672	what kind of political system is canada	  Canadians enjoy a parliamentary system of government. The Prime Minister appoints members of the Cabinet, who are responsible for various ministries.
